I Know not by what Fate it comes to pas, that Hitorians, who give immortality to others, are o ill requited by Poterity, that their Actions and their Fortunes are uually forgotten; neither themelves incourag'd, while they live, nor their memory preerv'd entire to future Ages. 'Tis the ingratitude of Mankind to their


greatet Benefactors, that they, who teach us widome by the uret ways, (etting before us what we ought to hun or to purue, by the examples of the mot famous Men whom they Record, and by the experience of their Faults and Vertues,) hould generally live poor and unregarded; as if they were born only for the publick, and had no interet in their own well-being; but were to be lighted up like Tapers, and to wate themelves, for the benefit of others. But this is a complaint too general, and the cutom has been too long etablih'd to be remedied; neither does it wholly reach our Author: He was born in an Age, which was enible of his vertue; and found a Trajan to reward him, as Aritotle did an Alexander. But the Hitorians, who ucceeded him, have either been too envious, or too careles of his reputation;


none of them, not even his own Country-men, having given us any particular account of him; or if they have, yet their Works are not tranmitted to us; o that we are forc'd to glean from Plutarch, what he has catter'd in his Writings, concerning himelf and his Original: Which (excepting that little memorial, that Suidas, and ome few others, have left concerning him) is all we can collect, relating to this great Philoopher and Hitorian.

Fautulus hearing Remus was taken, and deliver'd up, begg'd Romulus to ait in his recue, informing him then plainly of the Particulars of his Birth, not but he had before given him ome hints of it, and told him as much as an attentive Man might make no mall Concluions from it; he himelf, full of Concern, and fear of not coming in time, took the Trough, and ran intantly to Numitor; but giving a upicion to ome of the King's Centry at his Gate, and being gaz'd upon by 'em, and perplex'd with their impertinent Quetions, could not but dicover the Trough under his Cloak; now by chance there was one among 'em who was at the expoing of the Children, and was one imploy'd in the Office; he eeing the Trough, and knowing it by its Make and Incription, gues'd at the buines, and without farther delay telling the King of it, brought in the Man to be examin'd. In thee many and great Ditractions, Fautulus neither approv'd himelf altogether undaunted, neither was he wholly forc'd out of all: He confes'd indeed the Children were alive, but liv'd a great way from Alba; that he himelf was going
to carry the Trough to Ilia, who had often greatly deir'd to ee and handle it, for a confirmation of the hopes of her Children. As Men generally do, who are troubled in mind, and act either in fear or paion, it o fell out Amulius now did; for he ent in all hate a Meenger, both otherwie an honet Man, and a ure Friend to Numitor, with commands to enquire of Numitor, whether any tidings had come to him of the Children, as if they were in being; now the Man being come, and eeing how little Remus wanted of being receiv'd into the Arms and Embraces of Numitor, he both trengthned the belief of his hope, and advis'd withal to recover Matters with all expedition; and he himelf clos'd with 'em, and acted joyntly; the trictnes of time, tho' they had been deirous, did not uffer them to demur. For Romulus was now drawn very near, and many of the Citizens out of fear and hatred of Amulius, revolted to his ide; beides he brought great Forces with him, divided into Companies, coniting each of an 100 Men, every Captain carrying a mall bundle of Gras and Shrubs tyed to a Pole; the Latines call uch bundles, Manipuli, and from hence it is that in their Armies they call their Captains, Manipulares;
Rhemus gaining upon the Citizens within, and Romulus making Attacks from without, the Tyrant not knowing either what to do, or what Expedient to think of for his ecurity, in that Amazement and Ditraction, was taken and put to death. Amulius is lain. Thee are for the mot part the Relations of Fabius and Diocles Peparethius, (who I think is the firt that writes of the building of Rome) which ome upect are only fabulous and made Stories; but they ought not wholly to be disbeliev'd, if Men would conider Fortune, what trange things it ometimes brings about, and take an etimate of the Actions of the Romans, how improbable it is they could arrive at this Greatnes, had they not ome miraculous Original, attended with great and extraordinary Circumtances.

Their minds being fully bent upon Building, there aroe preently a difference Romulus and Remus differ about the Place about the Place where. Romulus he built a Square of Houes, which he call'd Rome, and would have the City be there; Remus laid out a piece of Ground on the Aventine Mount, well fortified by nature, which was from him call'd Remonius, but now Rignarius; concluding at lat to decide the Contet by a Divination from a flight of Birds, and placing themelves apart at ome ditance, to Remus, they ay, appear'd ix Vulturs, to Romulus double the number; others ay, Remus did truly ee his number, and that Romulus feign'd his, but when Remus came to him, that then he did indeed ee twelve. Hence it is that the Romans in their Divinations from Birds, do chiefly regard the Vultur, tho' Herodorus Pontius relates, that Hercules was always very joyful when a Vultur appear'd to him upon any Action, for it is a Creature the leat hurtful of any, pernicious neither to Corn, Plants, or any Cattel; it preys only upon Carrion, and never kills or hurts any living thing; and as for Birds, it touches not them tho' they are dead, as being of its own Species, whereas Eagles, Owls, and Hawks, prey upon all their own fellow-Creatures;
but Echylus ays,
< in non-Latin alphabet > ; What Bird is clean that preys on's fellow-Bird? Beides, All other Birds we ee (as the aying is) every day, and they occur continually to our enes, but a Vultur is a very rare ight, and you hall eldom meet with a Man can tell you how they breed, inomuch that the rarity and unfrequency of'em has rais'd an aburd opinion in ome, that they come to us from ome other certain Countreys, as Soothayers judge, what-ever happens preternaturally or inpontaneouly, to be ent from God.

It was the thirty eventh year, accounted from the Foundation of Rome, when Romulus then reigning, did on the fifth day of the Month of July, called the Capratine Nones, offer a publick Sacrifice at the Lake of Capra, in preence of the Senate and People of Rome: But then on a udden aroe o furious a Tempet, which, with black Clouds and Thunder rending the Air, made an eruption on the Earth, which affrighted the common people with uch confuion, that they fled and were dipered; In this Whirlwind Romulus diappeared, his The Fate of Romulus. Body being never ince found either living or dead. This accident gave occaion to the world to cenure very hardly the practice of the Patricians; as if that they, being weary of Kingly Government, and exaperated
of late by the imperious deportment of Romulus towards them, had plotted againt his Life and made him away, that o they might aume the Authority and Government into their own hands: but this report was oon confuted by the tetimony of Proclus, a noble peron, who wore that he aw Romulus catched up into Heaven in his Arms and Vetments, and as he acended cry'd out, that they hould hereafter tyle him by the name of Quirinus;
Whence nam'd Quirinus. which attetation gained o much credit in the minds of the People, that they ordain'd Divine honours to be perform'd towards him, as to one not dead but tranlated to a ublimer tate, above the condition of mortal nature.

Now the Cylonian villany had a long while diturb'd the Commonwealth, even from that time when Megacles the Archon perwaded the conpiratours with Cylon that took anctuary in Minerva's Temple, to tand to a fair trial; and they tying a thred to the Image, and holding one end of it, went down to the Tribunal: but when they came to the Temple of the Furies, the thred brake of its own accord, upon which, as if the Goddes had refus'd them protection, they were eiz'd by Megacles, and the other Magitrates: as many as were without the Temples were toned, thoe that fled for anctuary were butchered at the Altar, and onely thoe ecaped who made their application to the Wives of the Magitrates. But from that time they were call'd execrable, and hated. The remainder of this Faction grew trong again, and had continual quarrels with the Family of Megacles; now when the quarrel was at
height, and the People divided, Solon being then in reputation with the chiefet of the Athenians interpos'd; and by intreaty and admonition perwaded the Execrable to ubmit to a trial, and the determination of three hundred noble Citizens: Myron, the Son of Phlyeus, being their accuer they lot the caue, and as many as were then alive were banihed, and the Carcaes of the dead were dug up, and cattered beyond the confines of the Country. In the midt of thee ditractions, the Megarenians falling upon them, they lot Niaea and Salamis again: beides the City was diturb'd with upertitious fears, and trange appearances; and the Priets declar'd that the Sacrifices intimated ome villanies and pollutions that were to be expiated: upon this they ent for Epimenides Phaetius from Crete, Epimenides the Cretan. who is counted the eventh wie man by thoe that will not admit Periander into the number: He eems to be a pious man, skilfull in the method of Expiations and the rites of Religion; and therefore the men of his Age call'd him the new Curetes, and Son of the Nymph Balte: when he came to Athens, and grew acquainted with Solon, he ettled many things in order to his Laws: He made them decent in their worhip, abated their mourning, by ordering ome Sacrifices preently after the Funeral;
and taking off thoe evere and barbarous Ceremonies which the Women uually practied: but the greatet benefit was his cleaning the City, by certain propitiatory and expiatory lutrations; and by that means making them more pliable to jutice, and more ready to be united. 'Tis reported that looking upon Munychia, and conidering a while, he aid to thoe that tood by, How blind is man in future things! for did the Athenians foreee what michief this would doe their City, they would e'en eat it to be free; and ome report that Thales made the like conjecture, for he commanded his Friends to bury him in an obcure and contemn'd quarter of Mileia, aying that hould once be the Forum of the Mileians: Epimenides being much admired, and preented by the City with rich gifts, and coniderable honours, requeted but one branch of the acred Olive, and that being granted he return'd.

